AGI - This morning, before travelling to Brussels for the Extraordinary European Council meeting, the President of the Giorgia Meloni> will make a stop in Tunis. It is his fourth visit to Tunisia > in less than a year, the first in the Mattei Plan >. Italian sources observe how Rome continues to be "strongly committed to supporting Tunisia, a country close to us, with which we engage in historical relationships of friendship, and fundamental to the stability of the Mediterranean and North Africa. Italy - still underline the same sources - is also active in promoting positive relations between the European Union and Tunisia in support of the Memorandum signed on 16 July 2023. Cooperation between Italy and Tunisia is a global cooperation that invests the entire government action".
&nbsp;
The President of the Council will be accompanied by the Minister of the Interior Matteo Piantedosi>, the Minister of the University and Research, Anna Maria Bernini>, and the Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs Edmondo Cirielli > and in the coming weeks will follow further missions. The visit of Meloni, still observes the sources, "will allow to continue dialogue with Tunisian President Kais Saied> on the main areas of bilateral cooperation: implementation of the Mattei Plan for Africa, cooperation in migration and process of Rome, energy and economic cooperation. Cooperation in migratory matters remains a central aspect of the relationship between Italy and Tunisia and continues to be strong support at bilateral level and EU for ongoing efforts by Tunisia. It remains essential that the Tunisian authorities continue in their action against trafficking and trafficking in human beings and containment of irregular departures."
&nbsp;
"Italy - sources continue - is also committed to ensuring legal mobility for business reasons: on 20 October 2023 a Memorandum was signed between Italy and Tunisia in this area, the first of the nation. Tunisia is a priority country of the Mattei Plan for Africa. In line with the principles underlying this initiative (joint relationship, goal sharing, concreteness), the visit will allow an examination of the different areas of cooperation between the two nations".
&nbsp;
On the occasion of the visit will be signed three instruments within the Mattei Plan: an agreement on direct support for the Tunisian State budget in support of energy efficiency and renewable energies; a credit line for small and medium-sized enterprises in Tunisia; a protocol of Understanding between the Ministry of University and Italian Research and the Tunisian Ministry of Honour that will provide the framework for cooperation in this area between the two nations.
&nbsp;
"The Italian-Tunisia partnership - finally highlight the sources - fully invests the economic scope: Italy is permanently the first supplier and the second outlet market and are about 900 Italian companies active in the country. An ongoing strategic project is for the underwater electric cable ELMED, the first to connect the electricity networks of Africa and Europe, a pioneer of future investments in the field of renewable energies".

